INSERT INTO `link` VALUES (1,0,0,'Reflecting On The Original Big Idea For Moocs',NULL,'http://www.downes.ca/post/67865/rd',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=67865',NULL,NULL,1,' <br>\n		\n\nJames DeVaney, \nInside Higher Ed, \nMar 07, 2018\n\n		           \n		           \n\nThe announcements yesterday from Michigan and Rice have actually been in the works for a long time. The three-year \"Credits for MOOCs\" program \"allows students from the participating schools to enroll in specific free online courses from the other member schools and receive transfer credits for passing them.\" In this post James DeVaney, associate vice provost for academic innovation at the University of Michigan, describes the thinking behind the program. \"MOOCs and MOOC derivatives (e.g. Teach-Outs, specializations, MicroMasters, MasterTrack, etc.)&nbsp; are helping universities to expand how they think about engaging with the world,\" he writes. Related: Coursera introduces its first bachelor\'s.\n\nWeb: [Direct Link] [This Post]\n\n',1520439550,'yes'),(2,0,0,'Twitter Linguistics: A Study',NULL,'http://www.downes.ca/post/67864/rd',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=67864',NULL,NULL,1,' <br>\n		\n\nSerena, \nGoogle Docs, \nMar 07, 2018\n\n		           \n		           \n\nI hope that one day the author (apparently a high school student) gets appropriate credit for what is an insightful and clear study on five elements of Twitter linguistics: the keyboard smash,&nbsp;phrase capitalization, period insertion, excessively long ellipses, and comma ellipses. The author summarizes the study perfectly: \" I would like to note in my analysis is simply how complicated many of these linguistic phenomena are... there might not be a definitive explanation at all to why certain slang works and why others do not... online linguistic phenomena are not simple blips. As seen from this survey, they are extremely complex signified meanings masked by extremely simple and elementary signifiers.\" See also: Dude srsly? and The Language of Twitter.\n\nWeb: [Direct Link] [This Post]\n\n',1520439550,'yes'),(3,0,0,'More Than 120 Live Online Trainings Just Released On O\'Reilly\'S Learning Platform',NULL,'http://www.downes.ca/post/67863/rd',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=67863',NULL,NULL,1,' <br>\n		\n\nO\'Reilly, \nMar 07, 2018\n\n		           \n		           \n\nI don\'t normally post list of course offerings like this (so don\'t ask) but I wanted to highlight the business model here (I also wanted to complain bitterly about the use of the word \'trainings\' as a plural noun - the English language groans in agony). First, O\'Reilly is a publisher, not an educational institution, but they\'re moving into that territory. These are live online events, but the archives are stored and can also be used as training resources. Even more to the point, access is by subscription model only - they\'ll set you back $US 39 a month if you\'re a sole learner, more for groups. This is about the pricing average for these bundled services. I don\'t know what the subscription rates are like, but it doesn\'t take that many to turn into a substantial revenue stream.\n\nWeb: [Direct Link] [This Post]\n\n',1520439550,'yes'),(4,0,0,'A Quick And Simple Definition Of Microservices',NULL,'http://www.downes.ca/post/67862/rd',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=67862',NULL,NULL,1,' <br>\n		\n\nMac Slocum, \nO\'Reilly, \nMar 07, 2018\n\n		           \n		           \n\nThis article \"covers some of the basics of microservices: what they are, how they work, and what you need to keep in mind before implementing them.\" These are small autonomous services. The idea is that they work together in groups to produce ensemble effects. \" In a microservice architecture, the services tend to get simpler, but the architecture tends to get more complex. That complexity is often managed with tooling, automation, and process.\"\n\nWeb: [Direct Link] [This Post]\n\n',1520439550,'yes'),(5,0,0,'Carl Saganâ€™S â€œBaloney Detection Kitâ€: A Toolkit That Can Help You Scientifically Separate Sense From Nonsense',NULL,'http://www.downes.ca/post/67861/rd',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=67861',NULL,NULL,1,' <br>\n		\n\nJosh Jones, \nOpen Culture, \nMar 07, 2018\n\n		           \n		           \n\nI link to this &ldquo;Baloney Detection Kit&rdquo; to contrast the accounts of critical thinking that depend a lot on source and authority. Sagan (like most scientists) isn\'t having it. \"Arguments from authority carry little weight &mdash; &ldquo;authorities&rdquo; have made mistakes in the past. They will do so again in the future. Perhaps a better way to say it is that in science there are no authorities; at most, there are experts.\" And we all know not to trust the experts. More: Carl Sagan, Pale Bue Dot. Also: The Frontier is Everywhere. Sagan was always my hero.\n\nWeb: [Direct Link] [This Post]\n\n',1520439550,'yes'),(6,0,0,'Delivering Digital Change',NULL,'http://www.downes.ca/post/67860/rd',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=67860',NULL,NULL,1,' <br>\n		\n\nSarah Knight , \nJISC, \nMar 07, 2018\n\n		           \n		           \n\n\"Digital used to be an add-on to core business but those are days behind us, now,\" writes Sarah Knight. \"It\'s time for universities and colleges to stop treating digital as an accessory and to integrate it fully within all aspects of their business activities.\" This is in the context of introducting a new \'senior leaders briefing paper\' entitled Delivering digital change: strategy, practice and process (8 page PDF, with a lot of white space and images, because senior leaders don\'t read long things). There are key points in case even that\'s too much text, including helpful advice such as \"Leaders should develop confidence in their own digital capabilities, modelling the behaviours they want their staff to display.\"\n\nWeb: [Direct Link] [This Post]\n\n',1520439550,'yes'),(7,0,0,'What Are The Expectations Of Disabled Learners When Participating In A Mooc?',NULL,'http://www.downes.ca/post/67859/rd',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=67859',NULL,NULL,1,' <br>\n		\n\nPaul Feldman, \nJISC, \nMar 07, 2018\n\n		           \n		           \n\nI think this is a good question to ask but I\'m really not sure it was asked properly in this report. We read, for example, that \" disabled learners appear to be more interested in these subject areas: Society, History and Arts and Nature and Environment.\" Does that have anything to do with their self-identification as disabled learners? Or is it just a reflection of a small number of survey participants (which is not disclosed)? Do we really know that \"disabled learners are particularly interested in taking up MOOCs to determine if they can study at a higher educational level and to link to voluntary work?\" I\'m saying we don\'t. Image: MIT (I typed in the title and did an image search and this came up. Google works in mysterious ways.)\n\nWeb: [Direct Link] [This Post]\n\n',1520439550,'yes'),(8,0,0,'Over Sharing',NULL,'http://www.downes.ca/post/67858/rd',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=67858',NULL,NULL,1,' <br>\n		\n\nGarett Sloane, \nAd Age, \nMar 07, 2018\n\n		           \n		           \n\nThis item comes in the context of reports that people are sharing less content through social media - \"social sharing of content has been cut in half since 2015.\" It describes the phenomenon of people quitting Facebook because of fake news, relentless advertsing, and a general lack of value in a service that isn\'t even a record of anything. I quit Faacebook in September of 2016. There was a short-term impact on my connectivity but this effect has essentially disappeared. It helps that I publish on my own website, an it helps that I have smaller more personal communities I belong to. (Note: you might encounter a whitelist wall at Ad Age. Since I switched ad blockers from AdBlock Plus to Ublock Origin my problems with sites demanding I whitelist have ended).\n\nWeb: [Direct Link] [This Post]\n\n',1520439550,'yes'),(9,0,0,'Open Educational Resources In Tvet',NULL,'http://www.downes.ca/post/67857/rd',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=67857',NULL,NULL,1,' <br>\n		\n\nUNEVOC, UNESCO, \nMar 07, 2018\n\n		           \n		           \n\nSimple but very useful OER source list: \" On this page you find a commented list of platforms and services that provide or give access to openly licensed content for Technical and Vocational Education and Training.\" Three dozen sources are listed with short descriptions. More from UNEVOC. That is all.\n\nWeb: [Direct Link] [This Post]\n\n',1520439550,'yes'),(10,0,0,'If Youâ€™Re So Smart, Why Arenâ€™T You Rich? Turns Out Itâ€™S Just Chance.',NULL,'http://www.downes.ca/post/67856/rd',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=67856',NULL,NULL,1,' <br>\n		\n\nMIT Technology Review, \nMar 07, 2018\n\n		           \n		           \n\nI have always felt that great wealth is prima facie evidence of criminality. But this study (24 page PDF) suggests that another factor is involved: luck. It\'s certainly not intelligence, skill or hard work: there\'s no correlation between those factors and wealth. This article reportswork by Alessandro Pluchino and colleagues at the University of Catania in Italy. &ldquo;It is evident that the most successful individuals are also the luckiest ones,&rdquo; they say. &ldquo;And the less successful individuals are also the unluckiest ones.&rdquo;\n\nWeb: [Direct Link] [This Post]\n\n',1520439550,'yes'),(11,0,0,'What We Can Learn From Glosses And Research Into Glosses',NULL,'http://www.downes.ca/post/67855/rd',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=67855',NULL,NULL,1,' <br>\nPhilip Kerr, \nAdaptive Learning in ELT, \nMar 07, 2018\n\n		           \n		           \n\nA gloss is \"&lsquo;a brief definition or synonym, either in (your first or second language) which is provided with [a] text&rsquo; They can take many forms (e.g. annotations in the margin or at the foot a printed page), but electronic or CALL glossing is &lsquo;an instant look-up capability &ndash; dictionary or linked&rsquo;\". It\'s where the term \'glossary\' comes from. The question here is, do glosses help reading comprehension in language learning. But the more meta - and more interesting - question asks whether we can rely on meta-analyses to learn the answer to questions like the first question. \"We need to be cautious about using meta-analyses and effect sizes... we cannot necessarily assume that the findings of meta-meta-analyses are educationally significant.\"\n\nWeb: [Direct Link] [This Post]\n\n',1520439550,'yes');
